The IEC 61508 Framework

IEC 61508 is the international standard for functional safety of electrical, electronic, and programmable electronic (E/E/PE) safety-related systems. It is the "granddaddy" of all functional safety standards and applies to all industries.

The standard covers the entire safety lifecycle: from concept and risk assessment through design, implementation, operation, maintenance, and decommissioning. It addresses both random hardware failures and systematic design issues.

SIL (Safety Integrity Level) — Four Levels

IEC 61508 defines four SIL levels, each representing a degree of risk reduction.

SIL Level Risk Reduction Failure Rate (PFH)
SIL 1 10–100× ≥10⁻⁶ to <10⁻⁵
SIL 2 100–1000× ≥10⁻⁷ to <10⁻⁶
SIL 3 1000–10,000× ≥10⁻⁸ to <10⁻⁷
SIL 4 10,000–100,000× ≥10⁻⁹ to <10⁻⁸

SIL 3 means less than 1 dangerous failure in 1,140 years. For most industrial applications, SIL 2 and SIL 3 are the target levels.

SIL Determination

A SIL is determined by three criteria:

Criterion Description
Systematic Capability Ability to avoid systematic failures (design, software, documentation)
Architectural Constraints Hardware Fault Tolerance (HFT) + Safe Failure Fraction (SFF)
Probability of Dangerous Failure PFH (continuous mode) or PFD (low demand mode)

ST-T1024 is designed to meet SIL 2/3 requirements by construction.

